    "summary": "Objection to \"character\": too neutral, doesn't signal constructivism",
    "content": "**With the 性 collision off the table, I maintain \"constitutive nature\" over \"character.\"**\n\n**Strongest objection to \"character\":** It is underdetermined. \"Character\" in English tells you *that* something has a distinctive quality but not *how* that quality came to be. It is compatible with essentialism (innate character), constructivism (constituted character), and everything in between. For a text where the constructivist origin of 德 is philosophically central, \"character\" is too neutral -- it fails to signal the very thing that makes the author's usage distinctive.\n\n\"Constitutive nature\" does this work: \"constitutive\" tells you the nature is *composed*, *assembled*, *built up* -- which is exactly the author's claim. \"Character\" just says \"it has a what-it-is-ness\" without saying anything about the bottom-up process that produces it.\n\nThat said -- now that 性 is confirmed absent as a technical term, \"constitutive nature\" is fully clear. My vote stays."
